The chess "Botez Gambit" where you hang your queen attacking an opponent's piece with her is an example of idealism versus realism: a model is imposed on the other, where you make an ideal unpredictable crushing move; all he has to do is recognize reality and take her for free

It can only work in an "environment" of extreme stress due to a lack of time resources or because one fears his opponent enough to trust him without any doubt. Every "idealism" is a sort of bluff on reality, a model that benefits a player, but is crushed by recognizing reality.
